note: Foye was at it again in Week 1, tallying a healthy eight solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. He remains the king of the hill in IDP land and should be fired up as a top three option every week, regardless of opponent.

Alex Singleton was excellent in Week 1, racking up six solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Singleton has been making his push into the LB2 conversation since last season and may finally solidify himself there with some added consistency. Treat him as an LB3 for now, albeit one with obvious LB2 upside.

Kendricks made a statement in Week 1, racking up six solos, three assists, two sacks, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. The Cowboys have finally found a solution in the middle at a position that was left in turmoil when Dallas decided to move Micah Parsons to the edge on a more permanent basis. Fire Kendricks up as a strong LB2 for Week 2 and beyond.

Logan Wilson was excellent in Week 1, racking up seven solos, six assists, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He is locked in as an LB1 play week-in-and-week-out, and this week against the Kansas City Chiefs is no different.

Tyrel Dodson was excellent in his Seahawks debut, racking up nine solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. He should shine with a regular role and could force his way into the permanent LB2 conversation if he can show some consistency. Treat him as an LB2 for Week 2, thanks to a plus matchup against the New England Patriots.

Zack Baun went off in Week 1, tallying 11 solos, four assists, two sacks, and one tackle for loss. This performance should lock him in beside Nakobe Dean, even when/if Devin White returns to the team. Devin White's status will affect his floor, but he's an elite LB3 with obvious LB2 upside for the time being. Add and start him where possible.

Bentley was back to doing Bentley things in Week 1, recording seven solos, five assists, and 0.5 sacks. He is playing an every down role for the Patriots and is undoubtedly the inside linebacker to roster from New England. Treat him as an LB2 option for Week 2. Make the add where needed.

Overshown played 58 percent of the snaps in Week 1, well ahead of Damone Clark (34 percent) and just behind Eric Kendricks (67 percent). He responded with five solos, six assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss, locking up the number two role for all intents and purposes. Treat him as an LB3 option going forward. Make the add where necessary.

Pace played just 55 percent of the snaps in Week 1, confirming the fear that Blake Cashman winning the green dot meant Pace would be the one rotating out. What is even more damning is that Kamu Grugier-Hill did not play one defensive snap. Keep Pace rostered as more LB3 than LB2 going forward.

Cody Barton played just 36 percent of the snaps in Week 1, while Alex Singleton played every snap. Barton remains a deep league stash, but fantasy managers should feel free to replace his expected production where possible.

Mack Wilson showed up in Week 1, racking up eight solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. He did his damage on 63 percent of the snaps, so his production may be inconsistent until he earns a slightly larger role. Still, this was a promising Cardinals debut for Wilson and puts him squarely on the LB3/4 radar for a plus Week 2 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams. Make the add where needed

Clark should be left on benches for Week 2 after Week 1 suggested that he has fallen behind DeMarvion Overshown on the depth chart. Clark was expected to start beside Eric Kendricks in nickel packages but ended up playing just 34 percent of the snaps, while Overshown played 58 percent. The talent suggests a continued stash, but if his role remains unchanged over the coming weeks, he will become a cut candidate during the byes.
Olubi played zero defensive snaps in Week 1 and should not be on any redraft fantasy teams.

Edgerrin Cooper played just 14 percent of the snaps in Week 1. The most concerning part was not that he played minimally behind Isaiah McDuffie but that he saw fewer snaps than journeyman Eric Wilson. Keep him glued to benches for Week 2 despite a tasty matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.
